        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1887-09-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1887-09-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="697" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d697">
                <head>No. 697.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Straus</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1887-09-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">September</hi> 22,
                            1887</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 46.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your No. 24, of the 6th
                        instant, concerning the proposed law for the regulation of colporteurs, and
                        desire to say that you appear to have acted in-this matter very discreetly.
                        There is no objection to your associating the British embassador with you in
                        your efforts to secure satisfactory amendments to a law which in its
                        operations affect the interests of British societies as much as our own.
                        Your course is therefore approved, and a favorable outcome awaited.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">T. F. Bayard.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
